help emergency baby bunny question we found a baby bunny and it was by itself my mom called the vet and asked if that was normal anmd the vet said that mothers leave thier babies alone sometimes and my sister let the cat out because she thought it left but my cat now attacked the bunny so what should we do its an orphan do not take the bunny to a vet vets are for pets and most do not have the knowledge or experience to deal with wild animals do immediately contact a licensed wildlife rehabilitator you can find one here http www tc umn edu devo contact htm these people have the specialized training necessary to care for sick injured and orphaned wild animals they also have the state and federal licenses required to keep these animals until they are healthy enough for release which you do not have it is important to immediately get this rabbit the help it needs as most cat bites are fatal to bunnies it is going to need antibiotics and medical attention as soon as possible please ignore any suggestion to keep the bunny as a pet first of all it is illegal and secondly most wild bunnies die in captivity unless cared for by a trained professional Guinea pig Pet skunk Domestic rabbit Ferret Veterinarian Microchip implant (animal) Dog Rabies Fancy rat Cat First aid Bugs Bunny Tiny Toon Adventures Nurse KaBlam! Rabbit Hunting Tiger Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies filmography Who Framed Roger Rabbit Hamster Baby Blues Terri Schiavo Adoption Falconry Phoebe Buffay's songs Johnny the Homicidal Maniac Swift Vets and POWs for Truth Introduced species Fox hunting Feral child Dream Puma Traditional Chinese medicine Cheetah Breastfeeding Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Emergency Medical Services Feral cat Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Pet Elephant Myocardial infarction Socialization Tuberculosis Orangutan Episodes of Lost (Season 1) Zoophilia Tooth enamel H5N1 Animal rights The Care Bears Adventure in Wonderland Pneumonia Human cloning Mel Blanc European Rabbit Lib